result.execSummary:
The defendant Diamond S. Birt was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Attempt Strangulation and Suffocation [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Repeater, Domestic Abuse Assessments, Domestic Abuse], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.235(1).
  • Battery - Domestic Abuse Repeater [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Repeater, Domestic Abuse Assessments, Domestic Abuse], an unclassified felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes:
Defendant was ordered to report immediately to the probation and parole office. 
If Defendant is REVOKED, 82 days credit for time served.
Concurrent with: Probation is concurrent on Ct 2 of this same case as are the conditions thereof unless otherwise specified.

miscConds.notes: Defendant is ordered to pay the DNA surcharge, and to make arrangements to provide a DNA sample, within 48 hours, for testing through the Clark County Sheriff Department or if on probation, to the Department of Corrections as is required in all criminal convictions. Defendant is to pay costs, fines, surcharges or fees directly to and will be collected by the Clark County Clerk of Court.
The defendant is to submit to an Alcohol and Other Drug Assessment (AODA) and follow the recommendations, releasing the findings to the agent.

Defendant shall attend counseling, treatments, programming, evaluations as deemed appropriate by the agent releasing all records to the agent upon request and follow through. Defendant shall completed a Domestic Violence and mental health assessment and follow through.

The defendant shall have no contact with F.C. of any kind, whether direct or indirect, including in person, in writing, by phone, by e-mail or other electronic means, through a third party or in any other way, unless both victim and agent approve in writing. Defendant is to remain alcohol and drug free/maintaining absolute sobriety. 
Defendant is to remain in contact and comply with services offered and coordinated by Veterans Justice Outreach Coord.
The defendant shall not possess any weapons specifically firearms and knives, including and not limited to hunting knives. Defendant is allowed kitchen knives.

The defendant shall pay Department of Correction fees as directed by the agent. 

Defendant is to draft an apology letter to wife and children with approval by agent.
